  "topic_name": "Transpiration",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Transpiration is the loss of water vapor from aerial parts of plants, mainly through stomata. Stomata are pores bounded by guard cells that regulate their opening and closing. Guard cells open when they become turgid (take up water) due to potassium ion accumulation, and close when flaccid. Stomatal transpiration accounts for 90% of water loss. Factors affecting transpiration include light intensity, temperature, humidity, wind velocity, and water availability. The cohesion-tension theory explains ascent of sap: transpiration creates a pull (tension), and water molecules stick together (cohesion) forming a continuous column from roots to leaves. Transpiration helps in cooling the plant, transporting minerals, and maintaining water flow. Guttation differs from transpiration as it releases liquid water through hydathodes due to root pressure.",
    "rules": [
      "Transpiration: loss of water vapor from aerial parts",
      "Types: stomatal (90%), cuticular, lenticular",
      "Stomata open when guard cells are turgid; close when flaccid",
      "Potassium ion (K+) accumulation causes guard cells to become turgid",
      "Factors: light, temperature, humidity, wind, water supply",
      "Cohesion-tension theory: transpiration pull + water molecule cohesion",
      "Significance: cooling, mineral transport, water movement",
      "Guttation: liquid water loss through hydathodes (root pressure)"
    ]
  },
